p.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114586"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is admitted to hospital with cellulitis of his left leg. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and obesity. He takes metformin and gliclazide. On admission, he is commenced on intravenous flucloxacillin. After 48 hours of treatment, he develops worsening pain in his left leg and becomes febrile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His left leg is swollen, erythematous, and exquisitely tender to touch. There are areas of dusky discoloration and a few small bullae. Crepitus is felt on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 22 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein: 280 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 150 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start intravenous hydrocortisone","Urgent surgical exploration","Obtain an MRI of the left leg","Change antibiotics to meropenem","Commence heparin for suspected deep vein thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical presentation is highly suspicious for necrotising fasciitis, a rapidly progressive and potentially life-threatening soft tissue infection. The worsening of symptoms despite appropriate antibiotic therapy, along with signs such as severe pain out of proportion to physical findings, crepitus, and systemic toxicity, are red flags for this condition. In this scenario, \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent surgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. Early surgical intervention is crucial for both confirming the diagnosis and initiating appropriate treatment, which involves extensive debridement of necrotic tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging antibiotics to meropenem\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient in managing necrotising fasciitis. While broad-spectrum antibiotics are an important part of treatment, they should not delay surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObtaining an MRI of the left leg\u003C/strong\u003E might provide additional information, but it would delay definitive treatment. In suspected necrotising fasciitis, the need for urgent surgical exploration outweighs the benefits of additional imaging studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting intravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. Corticosteroids are not routinely used in the treatment of necrotising fasciitis and could potentially worsen the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing heparin for suspected deep vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this scenario. While deep vein thrombosis can cause leg swelling and pain, the clinical picture here is much more consistent with a severe soft tissue infection rather than a vascular problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, necrotising fasciitis is a surgical emergency that requires prompt recognition and immediate surgical intervention. Delay in treatment can lead to rapid progression of the disease, resulting in significant morbidity and mortality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Worsening cellulitis despite appropriate antibiotic therapy should prompt consideration of necrotising fasciitis.","Early surgical exploration is crucial in suspected necrotising fasciitis to confirm the diagnosis and initiate appropriate treatment.","Imaging studies may be helpful but should not delay surgical intervention if necrotising fasciitis is suspected."],"references":["Willems A, Shayan R. Necrotising soft tissue infection: A diagnosis not to be missed. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020;50(8):567-569. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/august/necrotising-soft-tissue-infection","Ge X, Sun Y, Lin J, et al. Diagnostic Key Points and Surgical Management of Necrotizing Fasciitis: A Retrospective Study. The International Journal of Lower Extremity Wounds. 2024;23(1):153-160. Available at: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/15347346211045282?icid=int.sj-full-text.similar-articles.2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96589"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20854"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20854"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SUSsDmrkaO8SKww6VKuz5DWwhAeUKY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SUSsDmrkaO8SKww6VKuz5DWwhAeUKY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96589"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T20:36:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T20:39:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6540"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114586"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":